			</li>
					<li class="list-item">
				<span class="widget-date">Story &mdash; 24 Jun 2015</span>
				<h4 class="title"><a href="/stories/how-providing-cash-helping-people-recover-nepal-earthquake">How Providing Cash Is Helping People Recover From The Nepal Earthquake</a></h4>
			</li>
					<li class="list-item">
				<span class="widget-date">Story &mdash; 16 Jun 2015</span>
				<h4 class="title"><a href="/stories/nepal-airlift-children-earthquake-hit-monastery">Nepal: Airlift Of Children From An Earthquake-Hit Monastery</a></h4>
			</li>
					<li class="list-item">
				<span class="widget-date">Story &mdash; 19 May 2015</span>
				<h4 class="title"><a href="/stories/nepal-operation-mountain-express">Nepal’s Operation Mountain Express</a></h4>
			</li>
				</ul>
	</div>
</aside></p>
<p>The World Food Programme (WFP) has mounted a massive response to meet the needs of the survivors of the two earthquakes that have hit <a href="https://www.wfp.org/countries/nepal">Nepal</a>, on 25 April and 12 May. It is an immensely challenging operation due to the mountainous terrain and remoteness of the affected communities. The focus&nbsp;is on a more long-term recovery. Some of WFP&rsquo;s response contributes to the country&rsquo;s resilient recovery.</p>
<h2>WFP has two main goals under its Nepal earthquake response:</h2>
<p>1) deliver food and other immediate relief to survivors, focusing on Nepal&rsquo;s hardest-hit areas which are also the hardest to reach,<br />
	2) provide logistics services to the wider humanitarian community to help them help the people of Nepal. This includes running a relief dispatch hub at Kathmandu&rsquo;s airport and field logistics hubs.</p>
